Linear Modelling

Create some random linear models to fit simulated data.

# Create some random linear model attributes
models <- tibble(
  m = runif(250,-5,5),
  b = runif(250,-20,40)
)

# Plot a simulated dataset and random linear models
ggplot() +
  geom_point(data=sim1, mapping=aes(x=x, y=y)) +
  geom_abline(data=models, mapping=aes(slope=m, intercept=b), alpha=0.25)


# Create model function
model1 <- function(a, data_x) {
  m <- a[1] # gradient
  b <- a[2] # y-intercept
  m*data_x + b
}

# Measure distance
measure_distance <- function(a, data) {
  diff <- model1(a,data$x) - data$y
  sqrt(mean(diff^2))
}

# Measure distance for all models
sim1_dist <- function(m,b) {
  measure_distance(c(m,b),sim1)
}

# Calculate distances
models$dist <- mapply(sim1_dist,models$m,models$b)

Show the models in model space.

# Show 10 best models in plot
ggplot() +
  geom_point(data=sim1, mapping=aes(x=x, y=y)) +
  geom_abline(data=filter(models, rank(dist)<=10), 
              mapping=aes(slope=m, intercept=b, colour=-dist), 
              alpha=0.25)


# Show models in plot
ggplot(data=models) +
  geom_point(data = filter(models, rank(dist) <= 10), mapping=aes(x=m, y=b), colour="red", size=4) +
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=m, y=b, colour=-dist))

NA

Same as before, except using a grid of model variables rather than random points.

# Create set of regular model variables
grid <- expand.grid(
  m = seq(0,5,length=25),
  b = seq(-5,20,length=25)
)

# Plot model variables
ggplot(data=grid) +
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=m, y=b))


# Calculate distance
grid$dist <- mapply(sim1_dist,grid$m,grid$b)

# Plot top 10 models
ggplot() +
  geom_point(data=sim1, mapping=aes(x=x, y=y)) +
  geom_abline(data=filter(grid, rank(dist)<=10), mapping=aes(slope=m, intercept=b), alpha=0.25)


ggplot(data=grid) +
  geom_point(data=filter(grid,rank(dist)<=10), mapping=aes(x=m, y=b), colour="red", size=4)+
  geom_point(data=grid, mapping=aes(x=m, y=b))

Plot Residuals

Demonstrate how to use linear models to plot residuals. Functions used:

  • modelr
    • lm(formula,data)
    • data_grid(data,var)
    • add_predictions(data,model)
    • add_residuals(data,model)
# Generate linear model
sim1_mod <- lm(y~x, data=sim1)

# Check model coefficients
coef(sim1_mod)

# Create input/output variables to model
grid <- sim1 %>%
  data_grid(x) %>%
  add_predictions(sim1_mod)

# Plot linear model against simulated data
ggplot() +
  geom_point(data=sim1, mapping=aes(x=x,y=y)) +
  geom_line(data=grid, mapping=aes(x=x,y=pred), colour="red")

# Add residuals to simulated data
sim1 <- sim1 %>%
  add_residuals(sim1_mod)

# Plot residuals
ggplot(data=sim1) +
  geom_ref_line(h=0) + #horizontal ref line at y=0
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=x, y=resid))

More Linear Models

Fitting models to continuous and categorical data

# Visualise sim2 data
ggplot(data=sim2) +
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=x, y=y))

# Fit linear model to this data
sim2_mod <- lm(y~x, data=sim2)

# Create input/output values for model
grid <- data_grid(data=sim2, x) %>%
  add_predictions(sim2_mod)

# Plot simulated data and predicted output values
ggplot() +
  geom_point(data=sim2, mapping=aes(x=x, y=y)) +
  geom_point(data=grid, mapping=aes(x=x, y=pred), colour="red", size=3)

Dealing two independent variables (categorical + continuous).

# Plot categorical + continuous variable data
ggplot(data=sim3) +
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=x1, y=y, colour=x2))

# Fit a linear model which looks at variables x1, x2 independently
sim3_mod <- lm(y~x1*x2, data=sim3)

# Create grid of input/output values to model
grid <- data_grid(data=sim3,x1,x2) %>%
  add_predictions(sim3_mod)

# Plot predictions on top of original data
ggplot() +
  geom_point(data=sim3, mapping=aes(x=x1, y=y, colour=x2)) +
  geom_line(data=grid, mapping=aes(x=x1, y=pred, colour=x2))

# Add residuals
sim3 <- sim3 %>%
  add_residuals(sim3_mod)

# Plot residuals
ggplot(data=sim3) +
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=x1, y=resid, colour=x2)) +
  facet_grid(rows=vars(x2))

Dealing with two continuous independent variables.

# Visualise data
ggplot(data=sim4) +
  geom_raster(mapping=aes(x=x1,y=x2,fill=y), interpolate=TRUE)

# Fit model
sim4_mod <- lm(y~x1*x2, data=sim4)

# Input/output grid for model
grid <- sim4 %>%
  data_grid(
    x1=seq_range(x1,5),
    x2=seq_range(x2,5)
  ) %>%
  add_predictions(sim4_mod)

# Plot output of model
# Top-down
ggplot(data=grid) +
  geom_raster(mapping=aes(x=x1,y=x2,fill=pred))
# Side-on
ggplot(data=grid) +
  geom_line(mapping=aes(x=x1, y=pred, colour=x2, group=x2))
ggplot(data=grid) +
  geom_line(mapping=aes(x=x2, y=pred, colour=x1, group=x1))

Non-Linear Modelling

Remember Taylors Theorem, which says every smooth function can be approximated by an infinite sum of polynomials.

# Simulate non-linear data
sim5 <- tibble(
  x=seq(0,3.5*pi, length=50),
  y=4*sin(x) + rnorm(length(x))
)

# Plot simulated data
ggplot(data=sim5) +
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=x, y=y))

# Fit 5 models to data
mod1 <- lm(y~poly(x,degree=1), data=sim5)
mod2 <- lm(y~poly(x,degree=2), data=sim5)
mod3 <- lm(y~poly(x,degree=3), data=sim5)
mod4 <- lm(y~poly(x,degree=4), data=sim5)
mod5 <- lm(y~poly(x,degree=5), data=sim5)

# Fit 5 more models using splines
mod1_2 <- lm(y~ns(x,df=1), data=sim5)
mod2_2 <- lm(y~ns(x,df=2), data=sim5)
mod3_2 <- lm(y~ns(x,df=3), data=sim5)
mod4_2 <- lm(y~ns(x,df=4), data=sim5)
mod5_2 <- lm(y~ns(x,df=5), data=sim5)

# Input/output data for models
grid <- sim5 %>%
  data_grid(
    x=seq_range(x, 50)
  ) %>%
  gather_predictions(mod1, mod2, mod3, mod4, mod5)

# Input/output data for models with splines
grid2 <- sim5 %>%
  data_grid(
    x=seq_range(x, 50)
  ) %>%
  gather_predictions(mod1_2, mod2_2, mod3_2, mod4_2, mod5_2)

# Plot model and data
ggplot() +
  geom_point(data=sim5, mapping=aes(x=x, y=y)) +
  geom_line(data=grid, mapping=aes(x=x, y=pred)) +
  facet_wrap(vars(model))

# Plot spline model and data
ggplot() +
  geom_point(data=sim5, mapping=aes(x=x, y=y)) +
  geom_line(data=grid2, mapping=aes(x=x, y=pred)) +
  facet_wrap(vars(model))
